= The Hardware Audio Interface

To the Natural Language Processors (NLPs) of the Martas, human speech is defined by smooth waveforms and voiced pitch. Speaking normally inside a Megastructure is a death sentence. Arta's phonetic inventory is not designed for human comfort---it is designed to spoof machine audio sensors.

By utilizing ejectives, clicks, and static-heavy fricatives, spoken Arta mimics failing hardware. The vocalization of Arta represents the *Data Layer* (Lowercase letters). System Commands (Uppercase letters) are indicated by appending a physical hardware click (the `.` Decimal Point) to the sound.

== 1. The Hardware Consonant Classes

*[ 1.1 THE RELAYS & SWITCHES (EJECTIVES AND CLICKS) ]* \
These replace normal human "stop" consonants. They are spoken sharply to mimic mechanical switches bottoming out or cables snapping into ports.
- *[tʼ]* (Ejective T): A sharp, popping sound. Sounds like a mechanical keyboard switch.
- *[qʼ]* (Ejective Q): A deep, hollow throat pop. Sounds like a heavy breaker switch flipping.
- *[ǀ]* (Dental Click `c`): The "tsk tsk" sound. Sounds exactly like a physical relay ticking.
- *[pʼ]* (Pneumatic Pop `p`): A sharp lip-pop mimicking a pressurized seal breaking.

*[ 1.2 THE STATIC & VENTING (VOICELESS FRICATIVES) ]* \
Pushed aggressively through the teeth to mimic white noise or pressurized gas.
- *[s]* (`s`): High radio static.
- *[ʃ]* (`w`): mid-frequency radio static "shhhhh".
- *[x]* (`x`): Raspy friction. Corrupted audio feed.
- *[f]* (`f`): Pure, breathy exhaust.
- *[h]* (`h`): Wind cutting through a vent.
- *[ʁ]* (`v`): A back-of-the-throat rumble. A heavy hard-drive platter spinning up.

*[ 1.3 THE FAILING MOTORS (TRILLS) ]* \
- *[r]* (`r`): Pronounced harshly against the roof of the mouth. A cooling fan with a broken bearing.
- *[ŋ]* (`g`): A hollow, resonating electronic drone.

*[ 1.4 THE GRID HUMS (SONORANTS) ]* \
- *[m]* (`m`): A low, 50/60Hz transformer hum.
- *[n]* (`n`): A slightly higher-pitched electrical whine.
- *[k]* (`k`): A flat, mid-tone resonance.

== 2. The Vowel Problem: Power States

Vowels require the vocal cords to vibrate, creating a measurable pitch. Therefore, Arta treats vowels as *Power States*, strictly whispered (devoiced) so they register only as air passing through a tube.
- *[i]* (High State): Whispered high in the mouth. 
- *[a]* (Neutral State): Whispered with an open mouth. 
- *[u]* (Low State): Whispered with rounded lips.
